               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc>
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>
                           <p>Octagonal <rs type="objectType">altar</rs> of <material>grey limestone</material>, comprising three separate pieces: 
               a square, moulded plinth (<dimensions>
                                 <width unit="metre">0.77</width>
                                 <height unit="metre">0.77</height>
                                 <depth unit="metre">0.28</depth>
                              </dimensions>) with a <rs type="decoration">circular socket</rs> in the centre of the upper face; 
               an octagonal shaft,  from face to opposite face; <dimensions>
                                 <width unit="metre">0.45</width>
                                 <height unit="metre">0.80</height>
                              </dimensions>), moulded at the foot and mortised into the socket of the plinth; 
               and an octagonal cornice-block, now much damaged (<dimensions>
                                 <height unit="metre">0.30</height>
                              </dimensions>), of which <dimensions>
                                 <height unit="metre">0.55</height>
                              </dimensions>, below the mouldings, is flush with, and forms part of, the face of the shaft below.
              </p>
                        </support>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>Inscribed on three faces of the octagonal shaft, on the front and right- hand faces in Latin, and on the left- hand face in Neo-Punic. 
               Texts b) and c) are closely related to <ref type="inscription">347</ref>, inscribed on the parapet which bounds the platform.
               a) On the front (die, <dimensions>
                              <width unit="metre">0.19</width>
                              <height unit="metre">0.68</height>
                           </dimensions>). l. 1, carved on the upper block, is missing, and ll. 2,3 and 6 overlap on to the adjacent face.
               b) On the right- hand face (die,<dimensions>
                              <width unit="metre">0.185</width>
                              <height unit="metre">0.33</height>
                           </dimensions>; about half of the text missing).
               c) On the left- hand face, Neo-Punic 32. The Neo-Punic text is a faithful transcription of the Latin of <ref type="inscription">318</ref> and <ref type="inscription">347</ref>.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>a) Capitals with incipient Rustic forms: <height unit="metre" atLeast="0.05" atMost="0.045">0.05-0.045</height>.</handNote>
                     <handNote>b) Capitals with incipient Rustic forms: <height unit="metre" atLeast="0.035" atMost="0.018">0.035-0.018</height>.</handNote>
                     <handNote>c) Neo-Punic </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
               </physDesc>
